In C++, you can start a new process and connect one file descriptor to its input and output using the `fork()` and `exec()` family of functions, along with file descriptor redirection. Here's a simple example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>
#include <stdio.h>
#include <fcntl.h>

int main() {
    int fd[2];
    if (pipe(fd) == -1) {
        perror("pipe");
        return 1;
    }

    pid_t pid = fork();
    if (pid == -1) {
        perror("fork");
        return 1;
    }

    if (pid == 0) { // Child process
        // Close unnecessary descriptors
        close(fd[1]); // Close write end in child

        // Redirect stdin and stdout
        close(STDIN_FILENO);
        dup2(fd[0], STDIN_FILENO);
        close(STDIN_FILENO);

        close(STDOUT_FILENO);
        dup2(fd[0], STDOUT_FILENO);
        close(STDOUT_FILENO);

        // Execute the command
        execlp("some_command", "some_command", (char*)0);
        perror("execlp");
        _exit(1);
    } else { // Parent process
        // Close unnecessary descriptors
        close(fd[0]); // Close read end in parent

        // Do something with the process, for example, write to it
        const char* data = "Hello from parent process\n";
        write(fd[1], data, strlen(data));

        close(fd[1]);

        // Wait for the child to finish
        wait(NULL);

        return 0;
    }
}
```

In this example:
- We use `pipe()` to create a pair of connected file descriptors.
- The child process uses `dup2()` to redirect its `stdin` and `stdout` to the read end of the pipe.
- The parent process writes data to the write end of the pipe and waits for the child to finish.

Make sure to replace `"some_command"` with the actual command you want to run in the child process.
